INTRODUCTION

Thalidomide, an anti-angiogenic drug approved by the FDA in 1998 for the treatment of Erythema nodosum leprosum (ENL) [], has been demonstrated to have anti-cancer properties [] and was used as a novel anti-myeloma drug for relapsed and refractory disease in 1999 [,].

To date, multiple myeloma (MM) remains largely incurable [].
('myeloma', 'remains', 'incurable')

Although originally marketed in Europe as a sedative and antiemetic, reports of teratogenic effects of thalidomide led to its withdrawal from the market in 1961[].
('reports of effects of thalidomide', 'led to', 'withdrawal from market')

The teratogenic activity of thalidomide was proposed to be mediated by its binding to both the DNA and RNA of the fetus, when administered either p.o. or i.p.
('activity of thalidomide', 'was proposed to be mediated by', 'binding to DNA')

Consequently, binding of the glutarimide moiety of thalidomide to DNA might alter the secondary structure of DNA [, ].
('binding of glutarimide moiety of thalidomide', 'might alter', 'structure of DNA')

Thalidomide was the first chemotherapeutic drug to demonstrate anticancer activity against myeloma in more than 30 years [], although the precise mechanisms of action of the drug remain undefined.
('Thalidomide', 'was', 'drug to demonstrate activity against myeloma')
('mechanisms of action of drug', 'remain', 'undefined')

Thalidomide analogs (IMiDs) are hypothesized to act through multiple mechanisms [], Lenalidomide has a better toxicity profile than thalidomide, and pomalidomide may overcome resistance to lenalidomide [].
('Lenalidomide', 'has', 'toxicity profile than thalidomide')
('pomalidomide', 'may overcome', 'resistance to lenalidomide')
('Thalidomide analogs', 'are hypothesized to act through', 'mechanisms')

A correlation between high plasma basic fibroblast growth factor (bFGF) levels and a positive response to thalidomide treatment in MM has also been demonstrated [].

bFGF is a growth factor that exists as several isoforms that differ in their N-terminal extensions, subcellular distribution and function [, ].
('bFGF', 'is', 'growth factor')

The expression of bFGF transcripts is under the control of a G-rich promoter.
('expression of bFGF transcripts', 'is under', 'control of promoter')

Our previous report showed that thalidomide down-regulates bFGF transcription and translation by targeting its G-rich promoter [].

The smallest low molecular weight (LMW) variant, an 18 kDa bFGF, is released by cells and acts through the activation of cell surface FGF-receptors, whereas the high molecular weight (HMW) (22, 22.5, 24 and 34 kDa) bFGFs localize to the nucleus [] and signal independently of FGFR [].
('weight bFGFs', 'localize to', 'nucleus')
('weight variant', 'is released by', 'cells')
('weight variant', 'acts through', 'activation')

Despite significant evidence documenting the expression and intracellular trafficking of HMW bFGF, many important questions remain about the physiological or pathological roles and mechanisms of action of HMW bFGF [].
('questions', 'remain about', 'roles')

The nuclear-targeted HMW 24 kDa bFGF may induce specific cell functions through intracrine mechanisms.
('HMW bFGF', 'may induce', 'cell functions')

The effect of nuclear bFGF on the metastatic potential of carcinoma cells demonstrated spontaneous metastasis in vitro and in vivo [, ].
('effect of bFGF', 'demonstrated', 'metastasis')

Interestingly, our data showed that thalidomide regulates the cellular distribution of bFGF in glioma cells [] and provides evidence for the role of the HMW bFGF isoform in carcinoma.
('thalidomide', 'regulates', 'distribution of bFGF')

Vacca et al. showed that the plasma levels of bFGF were significantly higher in patients with active disease than in those with non-active MM and MGUS [, ].
('plasma levels of bFGF', 'were higher in', 'patients with disease')

Anchorage-independent growth (AIG) is a hallmark of cancer cells [, ], and colony formation assay in soft agar was used as a simple selection method for human tumor stem cells [].
('growth', 'is', 'hallmark of cancer cells')
('assay in agar', 'was used as', 'selection method for tumor stem cells')

Since Hamburger and S. E. Salmon demonstrated a low percentage of clonogenic cells in the bulk tumor mass prompted a search for the CSC in MM [], colony-forming unit/clonogenic assays in methylcellulose or soft agar were commonly used to identify the MM stem cells [].
('percentage of cells', 'prompted', 'search for CSC')
('assays in methylcellulose', 'were used to identify', 'MM stem cells')

Our previous data have shown that the AIG of U-87 glioma cells was suppressed by thalidomide, and knocking down or even down-regulating bFGF expression is sufficient to decrease the tumor growth in vivo [].
('AIG of glioma cells', 'was suppressed by', 'thalidomide')
('AIG of glioma cells', 'is sufficient to decrease', 'tumor growth')

The ability to exhibit anchorage-independent cell growth is considered a fundamental property of cancer cells because it has been correlated with tumor cell aggressiveness in vivo, such as tumorigenic and metastatic potential [].
('ability to exhibit cell growth', 'is considered', 'property of cancer cells')

The majority of cellular stresses have lead to the inhibition of cap-dependent translation [].
('majority of stresses', 'have lead to', 'inhibition of translation')

Functional studies have demonstrated that cellular IRES (internal ribosome entry site) -mediated translation prevails under conditions when cap-dependent translation is compromised, such as hypoxia, heat shock, irradiation, apoptosis and tumorigenesis.

Nevertheless, the precise roles of IRES-dependent translation under physiological and pathological conditions remain to be determined.

Some mRNAs, however, are translated by a cap-independent mechanism, which is mediated by ribosome binding to internal ribosome entry site (IRES) elements located in the 5’-untranslated region.
('mRNAs', 'are translated by', 'mechanism')

These mRNAs code for products that include growth factors such as bFGF and VEGF, which are required for growth [, ].
('mRNAs', 'code for', 'products')

Some reports suggested the increased expression of several proteins that are under IRES control, such as oncogenes and growth factors involved in the progression of cancer [].
('reports', 'suggested', 'expression of proteins')

However, the role of the bFGF IRES in tumorigenesis has yet to be fully documented [, ].

Elucidating the mechanism of IRES-mediated translation and its regulation will be a major challenge in this field [].

In the present study, we examined the role of IRES-mediated regulation of FGF-2 translation in tumorigenesis as a critical step not only in solid tumors but also in multiple myeloma.

Using thalidomide as a tool, we elucidate its molecular mechanism in MM, compare the developed IMiDs such as pomalidomide, and highlight the right direction for developing more potent IMiDs with fewer side effects for MM patients.

